Part A: Case Study (Phishing Attack)

Title: Phishing Attack Targeting College Students

Phishing is a type of cybercrime where attackers trick individuals into revealing sensitive information such as passwords, OTPs, or bank details by pretending to be a
trusted source. One common scenario involves students receiving emails or messages that appear to be from their bank or a popular service provider.

In a typical phishing attack, the victim receives a message with a link that looks legitimate. When they click on it, they are redirected to a fake website that
closely resembles the original one. The user is then asked to log in or enter confidential information. Once entered, the attacker gains access to their account.

College students are often targeted because they frequently use online services and may not always verify links carefully. The consequences of such attacks can include
financial loss, identity theft, and unauthorized access to personal accounts.

Phishing attacks rely on urgency and fear, such as messages claiming account suspension or urgent verification. Being aware of such tactics can help individuals avoid
falling victim to these scams.


Part B: Prevention Checklist

🔐 Stay Safe Online – Prevention Tips
Always verify the sender before clicking on any link
Do not share OTPs, passwords, or bank details with anyone
Check website URLs carefully (look for HTTPS and correct spelling)
Avoid clicking on suspicious links from unknown sources
Enable two-factor authentication (2FA) on important accounts
Regularly update passwords and use strong, unique passwords
Do not install apps from untrusted sources
Be cautious of messages creating urgency or fear
For UPI safety: Never approve unknown payment requests
For UPI safety: Double-check receiver details before sending money

